In Antwerp 21 maij 1681
London Abrans vivian
Sr. my last to you was on the 13: curitt sence recd. yd of 2 ditto, by which
I observe that you have ordered the needfull for 9 babes of cloth, if you
finde the apearence so evident of rising the cloth lett mr. potter have yd
order for the resting 3 bales to make up in, for shall whnt them
& more, recommend yd freinds to buy no ve grayes principally
am onghnt the dolins & take rather modecolleurs, for them weewant
imost, so faile not to write this besides I have not given any order
yett for white kersies so please to in order the providing of 100 peeies
22 yd of the best some sorts red lists if possible & att least ½ of ayd &3
a 4 enckes broad, besides 50 & 60 kersies 30 yd broad peeces, red lists
of ⅓ of ayd broad, good goods for them sell best, so do not so much
lamitt prijses, butt oblige them to bay good & of best goods & assoone
as my ready to be curiously drest & prest (as nichipping didvere
well, & send to Hull to be dispatched for ostend in English vessels of
what passes in them affaires I long to know
I observe what you write concerning laces I am sorry you should
finde occasion to complaine, I wonder without ground should not
sell where as here yett is noless, nay more demanded then
others I do much wonder how in taylor should sell cheaper then you
where as wee are att the please where goods are brought to markett
& can pick & chose now what I please, so then to putt off the rest
have made a beginning to provide the parcell you order
uer not p l betdserce to momale espeteil mm
for I understand yd direction very well, except Antwarp laces, for there is
is no sort soealled, so pray send mee ap atturn thought butt of one nnck
long, that I may see what kinde of ground you meane: I have no newsg
ee yarht coming up here, butt if itt doth, shall endeavour to have itt
ready & to please you in all respects: I shall remitt without faile &
remaine with kinde salute
